Theresa May's Stage
London — — The task facing the newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May is a daunting one: to carry out the demand of the British — — or more precisely, the voters of England and Wales — — to "leave the European Union" and manage the significant consequences that this entails.
The challenge she faces surpasses that of any previous prime minister in recent years.
But she may possibly be capable of completing this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, Merkel has all the tools needed to complete the task.
She is smart and resilient, with no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very skilled at maintaining control, and operates within self-defined boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues at hand.
May has won in most of the battles she has participated in, and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded tactics against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination —— she needs to make full use of it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The Brexit process has already started, and there is no doubt about that.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that a Brexit referendum cannot go back.
She has repeatedly said, "Brexit is Brexit," and her ministers all agree with her view.
But Mei has not yet given an exact definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, “Breakfast is breakfast,” and then starting to prepare your food.
You would have a hard time clearly knowing what you are actually going to eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — paired with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people may focus mainly on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others might be more concerned about gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality often ignored by Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win favor or punish Britain for leaving the EU (sometimes such inflammatory rhetoric is prevalent, such as what the newly appointed British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson called "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone — including the EU and all its member states — has their own political or commercial interests they have sworn to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine what Britain's objectives should be after the difficult negotiations on the UK's relationship with the EU (and in the trade field, its relationship with the world) begin on a realistic basis?
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six separate topics that need to be negotiated), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter, who is 11 years old, may already be starting university!
) We must clarify the priorities in order to prevent the negotiations from taking even longer.
The goal is certainly to achieve a balance between British exported goods and services (especially financial services) entering other European countries and limiting the movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they will need to make in other areas.
Mary must make full use of the knowledge, skills, and political capital she has at her disposal to ensure the rationality of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that dissatisfaction is not only from a particular part — — such an outcome is inevitable — — but from all.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing the May government: narrowing the growing social divide in the UK exposed by Brexit.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have long been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called proxy — — the EU — — of globalization.
The English metropolitan areas — — especially London — — may benefit greatly from globalization, but they have not gained anything.
Many members of the working-class community have ultimately become victims of Brexit populist promises due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by Jeremy Corbyn.
“We will reverse globalization,” they said.
“We will drive out immigrants who suppress wages and redirect hundreds of millions of pounds that were sent to the EU into public services.”
They promised that Brexit would bring back a safer, more prosperous past for the UK.
Brexit supporters are unable to truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, just as it cannot cut off immigration from the EU.
Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
Even if the economic downturn leads to a decline in immigration, those workers who voted for Brexit may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public services remain under pressure.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already sparked an uncontrollable storm of populist sentiment.
Just as Donald Trump was powerless to improve the situation of working-class voters in the United States, the Brexit also completely fails to benefit those who chose it, regardless of how it may seem.
Although it has many advantages, such challenges may still be insurmountable.
